	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Proposal for a ban on fishing subsidies shocks Pacific island nations</h1>

			
			<h4>
												31 January 2006
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p> On January 2nd 2006, <i>Pacific Magazine</i> described the ‘shockwaves’ around the Pacific islands that rely on fishing as their major source of revenue, after calls were made by the ‘Friends of Fish’ for the WTO to consider a ban on fishing subsidies that may include fishing licenses and access fees.</p><p> But Australia and New Zealand, members of ‘Friends of Fish’ as well as of the Pacific Islands Forum say that the islands’ concerns regarding licenses and access fees have been taken on board.</p><p> This move by the 'Friends of Fish' prompted three Pacific island countries who are members of the WTO to submit a paper to it in July 2005, urging it not to include fishing licenses and access fees, which one authority estimates rakes in US$60 million to US$$70 million for the Pacific islands region each year.</p><p> ‘The “Friends of Fish” are still pushing for fishing subsidies that distort trade to be subjected to new disciplines or banned,’ explains the Pacific Islands Forum permanent representative at the WTO ‘but since the submission of our paper to the negotiating group on rules, consideration is now being given to give special and differentiated treatment to small vulnerable coastal states like ours in the Pacific. Discussions on this will continue this year with a view to adopting legal texts that hopefully will take onboard our position - which is to exclude access fees, development assistance, fiscal incentives to develop our fisheries sectors and assistance to small-scale fisheries - from the definition of a subsidy and therefore not banned.</p><p> ‘We understand that fishing licences and access fees are a major source of revenue for Pacific Island countries and other developing coastal states. This is why we have been very clear in the negotiations that we do not want to ban subsidies and licences/access fees’ said the New Zealand High Commissioner in Fiji.</p><p> Solomon Islands says it can only hope that promoters of the fishery-subsidy ban would stay true to their words.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p><i>Pacific Magazine</i>, January 2nd 2006</p><p>

<a href="http://www.pacificislands.cc/pina/pinadefault2.php?urlpinaid=19266" target="_self">http://www.pacificislands.cc/pina/pinadefault2.php?urlpinaid=19266</a> <br/> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> The issue of access fees for distant-water fishing nations, and the role of formal bilateral agreements that provide the legal and administrative framework for such access, have been at the centre of the WTO debate on disciplining fishing subsidies. At issue is the extent to which the ‘financial compensation’ provided by such bilateral agreements provides a ‘production subsidy’ to the distant-water fleet, thereby encouraging overcapacity, resource depletion and unfair competition for resource and market access.</p><p> This is a crucial issue for ACP small island and coastal states that rely heavily on these revenues for their national budgets. What is clear from the debate at EU level on FPAs, is that vessel owners should pay the full price for access to resources in third country EEZs. But that it is also appropriate that the flag state should contribute to establishment of a responsible fisheries regime in the interests of both parties. This will involve transparent earmarking of ‘compensation’ funds for particular activities to promote responsible fisheries (MCS programmes, fisheries research, etc) on the one hand, and higher fees for vessel owners on the other.</p>
		</div>
		
